  "prompt": "Why didn't PM Narendra Modi end reservation?",
  "response": "Prime Minister Narendra Modi and his government have not abolished the reservation system in India for several reasons:\n\n1. **Social Justice**: The reservation system was established to address historical injustices and discrimination faced by marginalized communities, particularly Scheduled Castes (SCs), Scheduled Tribes (STs), and Other Backward Classes (OBCs). Many believe that ending reservation would undermine efforts to achieve social justice and equality.\n\n2. **Political Considerations**: The reservation system is a sensitive political issue in India. It has strong support among certain communities, and any attempt to abolish it could lead to significant political backlash, potentially affecting the electoral prospects of the ruling party.\n\n3. **Current Welfare Programs**: The Modi government has focused on various welfare programs aimed at uplifting marginalized communities, suggesting a continuation rather than an abolition of existing frameworks to support social equity.\n\n4. **Public Support and Activism**: There is substantial public sentiment in favor of maintaining reservation policies. Movements and activism from various groups advocating for their rights ensure that the issue remains contentious and complex.\n\n5. **Economic Factors**: The debate around reservation also includes discussions about the economic condition of different communities. The government may recognize that disparities still exist and that some form of affirmative action is necessary.\n\nInstead of removing reservations, the approach has been more towards reforming and expanding the system, ensuring that it meets the current socio-economic challenges faced by various communities.",
